{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280601652/1937120801/0556.xml":{"full_text":"Ordnance for Four Vessels,\nJust Authorized, to\nBe Built Here.\nThe work load at the Washington\nNavy Yard will be benefited by the\nadministration's decision to construct\nfour new warships, costing $29,884,850\nin all. Assistant Secretary Edison,\nwho today started the program to get\nthem on the ways, said the ordnance\nfor the vessels will be constru;ted at\nthe naval gun factory here.\nTwo new destroyers will be built,\nene at the Puget Sound Navy Yard\nand the other at the Charleston (S.\nC.) Navy Yard, at a combined cost of\n*9.204,295, while the New York Ship\nbuilding Corp. of Camden, N. J., will\nconstruct a seaplane tender and a\ndestroyer tender, both to cost $20,\n680,555. The private shipbuilder,\nMr. Edison said in announcing the\nawards yesterday, following consulta\ntion with President Roosevelt, under\nbid estimates of the Norfolk and\nPhiladelphia Navy Yards, contrary to\nthe case of the two new battleships.\nThe Assistant Secretary emphasized\nthat the Navy is building these ships\nimmediately, in line with the Chief\nExecutive's desire that the Govern\nment spend available funds now to\nassist business revival and to aid firms\nthat build for the national defense.\n>ees Lav-otTs Halted.\nThe \u201cultimate lay-offs of thousands\nOf shipyard workers\u201d will thus be\nprevented, Mr. Edison said, in an\nnouncing the award to the New Jer\nsey shipyard. He explained that Pres\nldent Roosevelt has received many\nletters from school children in the\nCamden area, asking that the service\ngive jobs to prevent the lay-off of the\nworkers and award Government work\nto the firm.\nMr. Edison pointed out that Con\ngress has placed a limit of cost on\nthe two tenders and that under the\nlaw, the President is permitted to con\nstruct them in private shipyards, if\nthat is deemed desirable. In response\nto a query as to why the New York\nShipbuilding Corp. could underbid the\nnavy yards, when it did not do so on\nthe battleships. Mr. Edison said the\ndepartment did not have access to\nthe deliberations of the Board of Di\nrectors of a private corporation.\nSees Bid As Favorable.\n\u201cThe New York Shipbuilding Corp.\nsubmitted an extremely favorable bid,\u201d\nMr. Edison added. \u201cThe public inter\nest is well served in this, from the\nfinancial angle. If thus yard were to\nfold up, the national defense would be\nbadly handicapped. The bid is con\nsiderably lower than other private\nshipyards, and lower than estimates\nfrom navy yards.\u201d\nDescribing the awarding of the four\nvessels as \"strengthening the country's\nfirst line of defense.\u201d the Assistant\nSecretary pointed out, the geograph\nical areas of the Nation were taken\ninto consideration, because \"we try to\nkeep the work loads in all the navy\nyards up.\u201d\nThe destroyers each will be of 1.500\ntons displacement. The vessels will\nall be steam driven, Rear Admiral\nWilliam G. DuBose. chief of the\nBureau of Construction and Repair,\nexplained in revealing that the Navy\nhas rejected the bids for Diesel-driven\nmachinery.\nAccepting the bids of the New York\nShipbuilding Corp., under the adjust\nment provisions for rising costs of\nlabor and material, the Navy Depart\nment said that the destroyer tender\nwill cost $10,737,555, while the seaplane\ntender will cost $9,943,000. No division\nof cost as between the two navy yards\nfor building the destroyers was made\npublic.\n\nIZAAK WALTONS PLAN\nNEW SANCTUARY DRIVE\nLeague to Meet Tonight and Hear\nReport of Study of Plan's\nPossibilities.\nThe Izaak Walton League will re\nopen its campaign for a wild-life\nsanctuary along the Potomac River\nfrom the District to Mount Vernon\nwhen it meets tonight at the Ra\nleigh Hotel. A special committee,\nIncluding representatives from near\nby chapters, is expected to report on\na study of the plan\u2019s possibilities.\nDr. Paul Bartsch of the National\nMuseum heads the Wild Life Sanctu\nary Committee. Other members are\nDr. E. Russell Cook, Rockville; David\nLongneeker, Falls Church; Dr. Wil\nliam B. Holton of Bethesda-Chevy\nChase and Benjamin F. Stiffler, Sil\nver Spring.\nThe local chapter will be host Sat\nurday to the Regional Council of the\nleague. De Witt Harry, chairman of\nthe committee on Arrangements, will\nsubmit tonight a program for a busi\nness and dinner meeting.\nBRANCHES OF CENTER\nTO AID PLAN FOR POOR\nWill Accept Goods Given as Re\nsult of Mrs. Roosevelt's\nHouse-cleaning Scheme.\nFollowing a recent suggestion of\nMrs. Roosevelt that the American\npeople move their spring house clean\ning up to the Christmas holidays so\narticles found out of use can be\nturned over to the poor, the Com\nmunity Center Department an\nnounced yesterday that its branches\nover the city would act as collection\ndepots for goods collected by Wash\ningtonians who plan to follow the\nproposal.\nMrs. Elizabeth K. Peeples, director\nOf the department, said the various\ncenters would co-operate in the plan\nWith the District Congress of Parents\nand Teachers as distribution agencies\nfor clothing, shoes, furniture and\nother discarded articles which have\nbeen cleaned and renovated.\nMrs. G. T. Dowling has been ap\npointed chairman of an arrangements\ncommittee.\nRelief For The\nItching of Eczema\nft's wonderful the way soothlns, cooling\nZemo usually brings relief to Itching. Durn\nins skin. Often in severe cases itching\nU relieved when Zemo touches tender and\nIrritated skin. To comfort the Itching of\nSimple Rashes, Ringworm, Eczema and\nPimples, always use clean, soothing Zemo.\nIt should be In every home. Insist on\nSohnine Zemo. Approved by Good House\n(t* keeping Bureau. 35c, BOc, Jl. AU\ndruggists.\nfg ZEMO\nI\nPoetic Feeling Inspires\nKriesler in Recital\nViolinist in Superb Form\nAnd Holds Audience\nIn Rapt Attention.\nBy ALICE EVERSMAN.\nOCCASIONALLY an artist flncU himself in a superlative mood for a\nconcert performance and his playing becomes illumined with a\nfiner light than ever before. Such a mood was Kreisler's last eve\nning for his recital at Constitution Hall, under the auspices of the\nDorothy Hodgkin Dorsey Bureau A little over a month has elapsed since\nhe appeared here with the Philadelphia Orchestra playing then, also, a superb\nperformance. Last evening, however.\nne seemea to reel a personal inspira\ntion and a temperamental glow\nstronger than usual and a real pleas\nure in disclosing his ideas about the\nmusic program. His audience re\nsponded with that rapt attention\nwhich releases the restricting bonds of\ndaily thought settling dow'n to a\ncomplete enjoyment of what promised,\nfrom the first note, to be a superior\nperformance.\nIt is always interesting to re\ndiscover the many elements which\ngive to Kreisler's playing an appeal\nwhich no other violinist can equal\nand which no faults of intonation or\nsmall detects can undermine. One\nfinds a technique, first, that is remark\nable for a flexibility other than that\nwhich dazzles by its brilliancy, a\nmusical knowledge which specializes\nin analysis and a mentality, keen, orig\ninal and sensitive. There is never a\nmoment in his playing w\u00bbhen these\nthree are not functioning fully and\nharmoniously, each prominent in itself\nyet merging with Its companions.\nWhen warmed, as they were last night,\nby the fire of poetic feeling, the acme\nof artistry is attained.\nThe Bruch \u201cConcerto No. I In G\nminor\u201d which was substituted for the\nMendelssohn concerto, first an\nnounced, proved to be the high point\nof the program. It irradiated a\nspiritual quality of ethereal beauty\nclimaxed in the lyric Adagio in which\nthe artist surpassed many of his pre\nvious performances. The tone was\ndrawn forth, vibrant and pure, col\nored here and there with more power\nor melting Into a pianissimo of rare\nloveliness such as only Krelsler can\nfashion. It was not a cold thing\nof mental planning but a creation\nlrredescent with a sublimity that\ntouched a higher sphere of senti\nment. In this concerto, Krelsler dis\nclosed vistas of beauty which only\noccasionally one experiences In a\nrecital.\nHis program opened with a group\nof classics, his arrangement of Corel\nli\u2019s \"La Folia,\u201d Bach\u2019s \"Prelude and\nGavotte In E major\u2019\u2019 for violin along\nand the Tartini-Kreisler \"Fugue in\nA major.\" In the matter of under\nstanding of form and style, Krelsler\nU unsurpassed. There Is clarity and\nexactness without pendantry, for he\nhas countless small ways of em\nbellishing a classic phrase so that It\nbecomes alive with beauty. The co\nordination of his bowing and his\nAnger technique and the directing\nthought behind were particularly\nevident in his playing of the un\naccompanied \u201cPrelude and Gavotte.\u201d\nIn conclusion he gave a group of\nlighter numbers among which were\nhis own compositions, \u201cSicilienne et\nRigaudon,\u201d his arrangement for vio\nlln of Albenlz's \u201cMalaguena,\u201d Cyril\nScott\u2019* \"Lotusland\u201d and De Falla\u2019s\n\"Jota\u201d tranacrlbed for violin by Mr.\nKrelaler in conjunction with the late\nPaul Kochansld. Then followed the\nencores, quite as Important in a\nKrelaler concert as the printed -pro\ngram. For that vast audience which\nhad been enthralled for an hour and\na half, sat on, waiting to hear Its\nfavorite works with \u2019\u2019Llebesfreud\u2019\u2019\nand \"Schoene Rosmarln\u201d heading the\nlist.\nA great part of the pleasure of a\nKreisler recital Is the very sympa\nthetic background provided by Carl\nLamson at the piano and Mr.\nKrelsler and the audience eaw to It\nthat he had full recognition for hla\nachievement.\nForeign Chriitmai Topic.\nGeorge W. Grupp will speak on\n\u201cChristmas in Foreign Land*\" before\nthe Town Meeting Club of the Massa\nchusetts Society at the Wardman\nPark Hotel at 8:15 o\u2019clock tonight\nThe society\u2019s next dance will be held\nat the Wardman Park next Wednes\nday.\nI\nI\nHEHHifPlUBHED\nA Gift That Will Create Zest\nIn Both The Donor And Recipient\nd/zerru\nCocktail Jacket\nI Fashioned for moderns who are\nI aware of the better things in life\u2014\nX ond who insist on enjoying them.\nv Silky Faille\nand available in the season's\ni smartest tones.\n$12-95\nv Other Cocktail Coats\nBrocade\nFlannel\nVelvet\nS8.75 to,20\nSLIPPERS hard and$\n>oft soles_*\nNOW..FOR 5c A DAY YOU OWN THIS\nFeaturing 10 quart Waterless Cooker\nCooks 3 vtgetsblts ondo roost at tht somt timt\nNow.. every housewife can own\nthis beautiful complete set of Hamilton\nRoss Streamlined Eternity Matched\nAluminumware. A piece for every\nuse in the preparation o f every meal.\nA matched set made of extra heavy\nEternity Virgin Aluminum. The\nhandles are air-cool type. 24 pieces for\nonly $11.95...5c a day is all you pay.\nI Ensemble Consists of\n0 W\u00bbw4u Cooler-* pc. 4 Quart Covered\nWith vegetable com- Kettle 2 pc.\n\u2022partmerrtt and battle\nplate. fyf) I Quart Stew Pan. I pc.\n(g) Fry Pen Heavy gauge Stew Pan\nf** I pc.\n(P) 6 cup Percolator I pc.\n(ft Tea Kettle 2 pc. 2 Quart Stew Pan-1 pc.\n(f) Combination Cooler l7\" Owl\nand Rice Boiler pc. Koaiter 2 pc.\n(ft 6 Quart Covered French Fry Pan and Ba\u00bb\nKettle 2 pc. let 2 pc.\nmm For the J4 plecei\nIgE complete euhown\nI 5/ A DAY IS ALL YOU PAY\nj 500 Soto go on Sat* during this Special Offer.\nI Join our ETERNITY Aluminumware Club.\n\"ABC\" WASHER AND IRONER\nElectric Washer\nHere is the lowest priced finely built\nwasher ever offered a washer built\nup to ABC standards of high quality\nworkmanship and materials, and not\ndown to a price. The tub is finished\nin durable porcelain with French type\nagitator\u2014rubbing surfaces on wings\nand base. One-piece solid steel chassis\ni and full powered Westinghouse motor,\nmounted in rubber make it the sturdi\nest washer on the market.\nNo Money Down l\nElectric Ironer\nABC has built Into\nthis new low priced\nroll about Irone